  <title>triple point</title>
  <termversion>2.3.3</termversion>
  <lastupdated>2014-02-24</lastupdated>
  <definitions>
    <item>
      <id>1</id>
      <text>The point in a one-component system at which the temperature and pressure of three phases are in equilibrium. If there are p possible phases, there are p ! ( p- 3 ) ! 3 ! triple points. Example: In the sulfur system four possible triple points (one metastable) exist for the four phases comprising rhombic S (solid), monoclinic S (solid), S (liquid) and S (vapour).</text>
      <links>
        <item>
          <title>metastable</title>
          <url>https://goldbook.iupac.org/terms/view/M03872</url>
        </item>
      </links>
      <math>
        <item>
          <alttext>p</alttext>
          <latex>p</latex>
        </item>
        <item>
          <alttext>p ! ( p- 3 ) ! 3 !</alttext>
          <latex>\frac{p!}{(p\,-\,3)!\ 3!}</latex>
        </item>
      </math>
      <sources>
        <item>PAC, 1994, 66, 577. 'Definitions of terms relating to phase transitions of the solid state (IUPAC Recommendations 1994)' on page 593 (https://doi.org/10.1351/pac199466030577)</item>
      </sources>
    </item>
  </definitions>
